1. Definition of a commercial entity
Commercial entity: a for profit corporation bringing in over $10,000 in sales a year for over 90 days, with sales $ numbers calclated by any accurate method of your choice. 

2. Redistributability
Projects licensed under the Marican Community License have limited distributability. If you are a non-commercial entity, projects have free derivative redistributability as long as they are also shared under the Marican Community License. If you are a commercial entity, your rights are limited heavily. For internal use, you are considered a non-commercial entity. for use in commercial products, A "handshake" model is applied. derivitive works are not allowed in the traditional way, eg. a modified version of someone elses circuit boards. what is allowed is using this as a reference freely to create your own designs or modification kits for someone elses projects, eg a HAT for someone elses circuit board.

3. License intercompatibility
This license is not currently inter compatible with sny other outside licenses, although it is forward compatible with new releases of this license in the 1.X level , but not releases with a diffrent first didget like 2.X. if you want to make a intercompatible license, please contact me (Marican Engineering) through github issues and inter compatibility may be merged in to a future release.

4. Exceptions to limited distribution rights
Certain companies (eg pine64) that are considered for profit legally but have low profit margins and contribute to the open source community. our way of measuring this is through a bracketed system, if that company qualifies, they have to distribute their derivitive changes, similar to gnu, but can otherwise act as a non commercial, here are the brackets in max annual net income to profit margin:

10K-50K: 35%
50K-100K: 32%
100K-500K: 28%
500K-1M: 20%
1M+: 18%
